{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"24664147-a21a-4831-a152-b9d614687ad7","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** in Visual Studio (`File > Open`) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview). To convert for SpeedScope:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't on `PATH` in the container, find it (e.g., `C:\\Program Files\\dotnet\\dotnet.exe`).\n- For **EventPipe**-unaware scenarios or kernel-level data, use `dotnet-counters` first to confirm high CPU, then escalate to `PerfView` or `dotnet-trace`.\n- Add `--buffersize 256` if you're dropping events under heavy load.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2a91669f-bd9c-4eb4-a921-a6d44a829734","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":432},"id":"6354dbff-885b-4763-b199-2ee1f8f2102b","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:43:06.685Z","parentId":"027076b2-3951-4c03-ad54-cfa533c180a5"}
